These are :<br>
1. The neutron free paths length, and the probability<br>
of the neutrons splitting an atom before it leaves a mass<br>
of fissile fuel .<br>
<br>
2. A neutron will have a 100% probability of causing a <br>
fission if the radius of a mass of 100% pure fission<br>
fuel is 8.62 centimeters. A nuclear fission creates an<br>
average of 3 neutrons per fission event . In order to substain<br>
a fission reaction 2/3 of all the neutrons generated<br>
inside the fuel mass must cause a fission before they exit the fuel mass.<br>
<br>
3. Here is how the fission neutron mutiplier factor works:<br>
If 1/3 neutrons causes a fission the reaction dies out.<br>
If 2/3 neutrons causes a fission event then<br>
you generate 2 neutrons which causes 2 fission events and which produces 6 more neutrons, then 4 of those  neutrons causes  4 fissions, then the release of 12 neutrons and 8 additional fission events occurr : then 16/24 neutrons are released which causes 16 more fission events and releases 48 neutrons  which cause 32 more fission events and so on.When this condition exists :  you have a critical mass, and there will be a self sustaining, fission chain reaction which accelerates itself expoentially. The atomic reactor core or the A-bomb core is now supercritical. To achieve 2/3 * 100 = which is 67% probability that each neutron will cause a fission event the radius of the atomic core must be   67% of the neutron free path. I will now round this figure off to 70% <br>
 iThis requires about a  6 centimeters radius  for 100% pure U 235 or Pu 239.<br>
<br>
4. Therefore to make an A-bomb core you need about a 12 centimeter diameter solid sphere or cube of 100% pure fissile material.<br>
<br>
 5.If the purity is 80% however you then need a core with<br>
a 7.54 centimeter radius, and a 15.08 centimeter diameter.<br>
<br>
6.The density Of U 235, U 233,and Pu 239 is about 19 grams per cubic centimeter. If we use a cube made of 80% heu or Pu239  to simplifly the critical mass   calculation,  we find that 15.08 cubed * 19 grams  =65,156.482 grams.<br>
<br>
7. In kilograms this is 65.156 kilograms of 80% heu to make the critical mass.If we use 100% Heu Then 52.125 kilograms is required to achieve a bare critical mass with no tamper or neutron reflecter.<br>
<br>
8. If I want to fuel an atomic  reactor with 5% heu or Pu 239  then the bare metal critical mass  is calculated to be 1042.5 kilograms.This method 1 to achieve criticalty which is <br>
to put a l;arge enough mass of fuel together. This applies<br>
to fission reactors and gun type A-bombs.<br>
<br>
9. The other method to achieve criticalty is to increase<br>
the density of the fission fuel by compressing it to shove<br>
the fissile atoms closer together. If I have a mass of fuel that<br>
has a radius of 4.31 centimeters, and a diameter of 8.62<br>
centimeters I can make it supercritical by doubling the density<br>
of the fuel. <br>
<br>
  10.If I do this I increase the probability that each <br>
neutron will cause a fission by a factor of 2 from 50 % to<br>
100%. This is the the atomic physics principle that makes<br>
Implosion type A-bombs possible <br>
